'Olympic National Park' is a United States national park located in the state of
Washington, in the Olympic Peninsula. The park has four basic regions: the
Pacific coastline, alpine areas, the west side temperate rainforest and the
forests of the drier east side.

U.S. President Theodore Roosevelt originally created Mount Olympus National
Monument in 1909. It was designated a national park by President
Franklin Roosevelt on June 29, 1938. In 1976, Olympic National Park became an
International Biosphere Reserve, and in 1981 it was designated a World Heritage
Site. In 1988, Congress designated 95 percent of the park as the Olympic
Wilderness.
